{{about|the broadcast||All Points Bulletin (disambiguation)}}
An '''all-points bulletin''' ('''APB''') is a [[Broadcasting|broadcast]] issued from any [[List of United States state and local law enforcement agencies|American]] or [[List of law enforcement agencies in Canada|Canadian]] law enforcement agency to its personnel, or to other law enforcement agencies. It typically contains information about a wanted [[suspect]] who is to be arrested or a [[person of interest]], for whom law enforcement officers are to look. They are usually dangerous or missing persons. As used by American police, the term dates to at least 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=APB |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |date= |accessdate=2018-09-07}}</ref>
An all-points bulletin can also be known as a '''BOLO''' or '''BOL''', which stands for "be on (the) look-out". Such an alert may also be called a '''lookout''' or '''ATL''' ("attempt to locate").
==Other countries== A similar, longer acronym used by Australian law enforcement is '''KALOF''' or '''KLO4''' (for "'''keep a look-out for'''"). The United Kingdom uses a similar system known as the '''all-ports warning''' or '''APW''', which circulates a suspect's description to airports, ports and international railway stations to detect an offender or suspect leaving the country. Because of the great numbers of commuters at such places, British police forces often prefer to contact specific airports, ports or stations and circulate descriptions individually.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.policespecials.com/forum/index.php?showtopic=47046&st=0&gopid=927104& |title=All Points Bulletin/All Ports Warning |publisher=Police Specials |date= |accessdate=2010-06-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519011808/http://www.policespecials.com/forum/index.php?showtopic=47046&st=0&gopid=927104& |archivedate=2009-05-19 }}</ref>
