{{redirect|Bleeding edge|the novel|Bleeding Edge}} {{For|the [[Powered exoskeleton|armor]] of the same name, belonging to fictional [[Marvel Comics]] character [[Iron Man]]|Bleeding Edge Armor}} '''Bleeding edge technology''' is a category of [[technology|technologies]] so new that they could have a high risk of being unreliable and lead adopters to incur greater expense in order to make use of them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/bleeding%20edge |title=bleeding edge. (n.d.) |website=Dictionary.com Unabridged |publisher=Random House |accessdate=12 September 2008}}</ref><ref name="Oz2008"/> The term ''bleeding edge'' was formed as an [[allusion]] to the similar terms "leading edge" and "[[wikt:cutting edge|cutting edge]]". It tends to imply even greater advancement, albeit at an increased risk because of the unreliability of the [[software]] or [[Computer hardware|hardware]].<ref name="SchommerBroschart2010">{{cite book |author1=Ingo Schommer |author2=Steven Broschart |title=SilverStripe: The Complete Guide to CMS Development |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pKBbDyyiCokC&pg=PR22 |accessdate=14 December 2011 |date=7 January 2010 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=978-0-470-68270-8 |page=22}}</ref> The first documented example of this term being used dates to early 1983, when an unnamed banking executive was quoted to have used it in reference to [[Storage Technology Corporation]].<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite news |last=Hayes |first=Thomas C. |title=Hope at Storage Technology |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/03/21/business/hope-at-storage-technology.html |accessdate=10 September 2013 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=21 March 1983}}</ref>
By its nature, a proportion of bleeding edge technology will make it into the mainstream. For example, [[electronic mail]] (email) was once considered to be bleeding edge.<ref name="Infosystems">{{cite book |title=Infosystems |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v1JUAAAAMAAJ |accessdate=14 December 2011 |year=1977 |publisher=Hitchcock Pub. Co. |page=64}}</ref>
==Criteria== A technology may be considered bleeding edge where it contains a degree of risk, or, more generally, there is a significant downside to early adoption, such as: *''Lack of consensus'' &ndash; competing ways of doing new things exist and there is little to no indication in which direction the market will go.{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}} By its very nature, consumers and firms will be unfamiliar with the product and its relationship to existing technologies,<ref name="Oz2008"/> leading to rapid changes in what is considered best practice as more becomes known about the technology's qualities.<ref name="SchommerBroschart2010"/> *''Lack of testing'' &ndash; The technology may be unreliable,<ref name="Oz2008"/> or simply untested.<ref name="SchommerBroschart2010"/> *''Industry resistance to change'' &ndash; trade journals and industry leaders have spoken against a new technology or product but some organizations are trying to implement it anyway because they are convinced it is technically superior.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}
==Costs and benefits== The rewards for successful early adoption of new technologies can be great in terms of establishing a [[comparative advantage]] in otherwise competitive markets;<ref name="Oz2008">{{cite book |author=Effy Oz |title=Management Information Systems |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fATar8Nn6HEC&pg=PA65 |accessdate=9 November 2010 |date=23 January 2008 |publisher=Cengage Learning |isbn=978-1-4239-0178-5 |page=65}}</ref> unfortunately, the penalties for "betting on the wrong horse" (e.g. in a [[format war]]) or choosing the wrong product are equally large. Whenever an organization decides to take a chance on bleeding edge technology there is a chance that they will be stuck with a [[white elephant]] or worse.
Bleeding edge computer software, especially [[open source software]], is especially common. Indeed, it is usual practice for open-source [[software developer|developers]] to release new, bleeding edge, versions of their software fairly frequently, sometimes in a rather [[work-in-progress|unpolished state]] to allow others to review, test, and, in many cases, contribute to it ([[beta testing]]). Therefore, users who want features that have not been implemented in older, more [[Software release life cycle#Release|stable releases]] of the software are able to choose the bleeding-edge version. In such cases, the user is willing to sacrifice stability, reliability, or ease of use for the sake of increased functionality.<ref name="Inc.2000">{{cite journal |last=Rikishi |first=Niramiai |title=Selling in the Bazaar: How Open Source Manages Code |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZpoOEa4kiSIC&pg=PA41 |journal=AAUGN |accessdate=9 November 2010 |date=December 2000 |publisher=AUUG, Inc. |page=41}}</ref>
