{{for|the village in Iran|Hafta, Iran}} {{See Wiktionary||hafta|meaning of the word}} '''Hafta''' ([[Persian language|Persian]]: هفته) is the Persian word for [[week]] and is also used as a loanword in [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Sylheti language|Sylheti]], [[Urdu]] and [[Turkish language|Turkish]]. A week has seven days, and is possible that it could be from Hepta, for seven.
'''Hafta''' ([[Devanagari]]: हफ़्ता) is also [[slang]] for the [[protection money]] collected periodically by gangsters and corrupt policemen. In case of policemen, however even bribes paid are often quoted as giving ''hafta.''<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ipaidabribe.com/reports/paid/paying-rs-25000-monthly-hafta-police-our-restaurant|title = Paying Rs 25,000 monthly hafta to police for our restaurant|website = www.ipaidabribe.com|access-date = 2016-04-15}}</ref> This meaning seems to have gained its popularity because of its usage as part of [[Bombay Hindi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://sidthebohemian.deviantart.com/art/Mumbai-Slang-47881860|title = Mumbai Slang|website = sidthebohemian.deviantart.com|access-date = 2016-04-15}}</ref> It is named so because the most common collection period is one week. The practice is highly prevalent in [[India]] and a refusal to pay up has its consequences.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.aamboli.com/translate/%25E0%25A4%25B9%25E0%25A4%25AB%25E0%25A4%25BC%25E0%25A5%258D%25E0%25A4%25A4%25E0%25A4%25BE|title = हफ़्ता- Translation, Meaning in Hindi, Thesaurus, Shabdkosh, examples.|last = AamBoli.com|website = www.aamboli.com|access-date = 2016-04-15}}</ref><ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20031006/ldh1.htm Refusing ‘hafta’ to cop costs shoemaker his life]</ref>
==In popular culture== ''Hafta'' has been used in the title of low-budget action movies in [[Bollywood]]. Some of the examples include movies like ''[[Hafta Vasuli]]'' (1998), ''[[Hafta Bandh]]'' (1991).
